{
  "doc_id": "16382",
  "text": "Agonistic interactions, which result in increased distance between two opponents through spontaneous displacement, noncontact or physical aggression, can be prevented by ritualized interactions [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Indeed, combat is typically preceded by ritual, threat display and mutual assessment using information about fighting ability from visual, olfactory or acoustical signals [CITATION_3] . For example, information about familiarity is present in auditory signals such as vocalisations and in olfactory cues, available through behaviour such as dung sniffing [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . As in many other ungulates (e.g. fallow deer, Dama dama [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] ; red deer, Cervus elaphus [CITATION_8] ), vocalisations also provide information about individuality, body size and dominance status [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] . Ritualized displays, which refer to interactions that do no longer keep their initial function, are common between stallions [CITATION_12] [CITATION_13] [CITATION_14] . These displays typically show a decrease in intensity and duration with time, and seem to facilitate stallions being able to graze side-byside [CITATION_15] . They play an important role in establishing and maintaining the hierarchy without involving physical aggression [CITATION_16] [CITATION_17] .",
